gaap:OrganizationConsolidationBasisOfPresentationBusinessDescriptionAndAccountin
gPoliciesTextBlock contextRef="From2014-04-01to2014-06-30">&lt;p style="font: 
10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-
left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;&lt;b&gt;Note&#13;1 &amp;#150; Business 
Organization&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Organization&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;Rancher&#13;Energy Corp. (&amp;#147;Rancher Energy&amp;#148; or the 
&amp;#147;Company&amp;#148;) formerly known as Metalex Resources, Inc. 
(&amp;#147;Metalex&amp;#148;)&#13;was incorporated in Nevada on 
February&amp;#160;4, 2004.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-
left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;Metalex&#13;was formed for the purpose of acquiring, exploring and 
developing mining properties. On April&amp;#160;18, 2006, the 
stockholders&#13;of Metalex voted to change its name to Rancher Energy Corp. and
announced that it changed its business plan and focus from mining&#13;to oil and
gas.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:OrganizationConsolidationBasisOfPresentationBusinessDescriptionAndAccountin
gPoliciesTextBlock>
    <us-gaap:SignificantAccountingPoliciesTextBlock contextRef="From2014-04-
01to2014-06-30">&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: 
justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;b&gt;Note&#13;2 &amp;#150; Summary of 
Significant Accounting Policies &lt;/b&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p
style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Use&#13;of Estimates in the Preparation of Financial 
Statements&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;The&#13;preparation of financial statements in conformity with 
accounting principles generally accepted in the United States 
requires&#13;management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the 
reported amounts of assets and liabilities, disclosure of contingent&#13;assets 
and liabilities at the date of the financial statements, and the reported 
amounts of revenues and expenses during the reporting&#13;periods. Actual 
results could differ from those estimates.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p
style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Cash&#13;and Cash
Equivalents&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
10pt/11pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; 
margin-left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;The&#13;Company considers all liquid investments purchased with an 
initial maturity of three months or less to be cash equivalents. Cash&#13;and 
cash equivalents include demand deposits and money market funds carried at cost 
which approximates fair value. The Company&#13;maintains its cash in 
institutions insured by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation 
(&amp;#147;FDIC&amp;#148;), although such deposits&#13;are in excess of the 
insurance coverage. At June 30, 2014, the Company had $1,139,299 in cash 
deposits in excess of FDIC 
insured&#13;limits.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Oil&#13;and Gas Producing 
Activities&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;The&#13;Company has only recently re-engaged in oil and gas producing 
activities. In accounting for oil and gas producing activities,&#13;the Company 
uses the successful efforts method of accounting for its oil and gas properties.
Under this method of accounting,&#13;all property acquisition costs and costs of
exploratory and development wells are capitalized when incurred, pending 
determination&#13;of whether the well has found proved reserves. If an 
exploratory well does not find proved reserves, the costs of drilling 
the&#13;well are charged to expense. Exploratory dry hole costs are included in 
cash flows from investing activities as part of capital&#13;expenditures within 
the consolidated statements of cash flows. The costs of development wells are 
capitalized whether or not proved&#13;reserves are found. Costs of unproved 
leases, which may become productive, are reclassified to proved properties when 
proved reserves&#13;are discovered on the property. Unproved oil and gas 
interests are carried at the lower of cost or estimated fair value and 
are&#13;not subject to amortization&lt;b&gt;. &lt;/b&gt;At June 30, 2014 and 
March 31, 2014, the Company had $0 and $0, respectively of unproved oil&#13;and 
gas properties.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times 
New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;Geological&#13;and geophysical costs and the costs of carrying and 
retaining unproved properties are expensed as incurred. DD&amp;#38;A of 
capitalized&#13;costs related to proved oil and gas properties is calculated on 
a property-by-property basis using the units-of-production method&#13;based upon
proved reserves. The computation of DD&amp;#38;A takes into consideration 
restoration, dismantlement, and abandonment costs&#13;and the anticipated 
proceeds from salvaging equipment.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;The&#13;Company complies with ASC 932, &amp;#147;Extractive Activities
&amp;#150; Oil and Gas&amp;#148;. As of June 30, 2014 and March 31, 
2014,&#13;the Company did not have any existing capitalized exploratory well 
costs, and has therefore determined that there are no suspended&#13;well costs 
that should be impaired.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt
Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;The&#13;Company reviews its long-lived assets for impairments when 
events or changes in circumstances indicate that impairment may 
have&#13;occurred. The impairment test for proved properties compares the 
expected undiscounted future net cash flows on a property-by-property&#13;basis 
with the related net capitalized costs, including costs associated with asset 
retirement obligations, at the end of each&#13;reporting period. Expected future
cash flows are calculated on all proved reserves using a discount rate and price
forecasts selected&#13;by the Company&amp;#146;s management. The discount rate 
is a rate that management believes is representative of current market 
conditions.&#13;Operating costs are also adjusted as deemed appropriate for 
these estimates. When the net capitalized costs exceed the
undiscounted&#13;future net revenues of a field, the cost of the field is 
reduced to fair value, which is determined using discounted future 
net&#13;revenues. An impairment allowance is provided on unproved property when 
the Company determines the property will not be developed&#13;or the carrying 
value is not realizable. At June 30, 2014 and March 31, 2014, the Company did 
not have any proved oil and 
gas&#13;properties.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Property&#13;and 
Equipment&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;Property&#13;and equipment, such as office furniture and equipment, 
and computer hardware and software, are recorded at cost. Costs of 
renewals&#13;and improvements that substantially extend the useful lives of the 
assets are capitalized. Maintenance and repair costs are expensed&#13;when 
incurred. Depreciation is calculated using the straight-line method over the 
estimated useful lives of the assets from five&#13;to ten years. When other 
property and equipment is sold or retired, the capitalized costs and related 
accumulated depreciation&#13;are removed from their respective accounts. 
Depreciation expense for the three months ended June 30, 2014 and 2013 was 
$8,316&#13;and $8,316, respectively.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Revenue&#13;Recognition&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;
&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-
right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif"&gt;The&#13;Company currently has no revenue from operations 
although during the three months ended June 30, 2014 and 2013, respectively 
the&#13;Company did have a nominal amount of interest received from financial 
institutions for funds on deposit.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Income&#13;Taxes&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&l
t;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;The&#13;Company uses the liability method of accounting for income 
taxes under which deferred tax assets and liabilities are recognized&#13;for the
future tax consequences of temporary differences between the accounting bases 
and the tax bases of the Company&amp;#146;s&#13;assets and liabilities. The 
deferred tax assets and liabilities are computed using enacted tax rates in 
effect for the year in&#13;which the temporary differences are expected to 
reverse.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New 
Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;The&#13;Company assessed the likelihood of utilization of the deferred
tax assets in light of recent and expected continuing losses. As&#13;a result of
this review, the deferred tax asset of $31,585,000 has been fully reserved at 
June 30, 2014. At June 30, 2014, the&#13;Company had net operating
 loss carryforwards of approximately $86,706,000 that begin to expire in the 
year 2023.&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;The&#13;Company adopted the provisions of ASC 740, &amp;#147;Income 
Taxes&amp;#148; on April&amp;#160;1, 2007. FASB ASC 740 provides detailed 
guidance&#13;for the financial statement recognition, measurement and disclosure
of uncertain tax positions recognized in the financial statements.&#13;Tax 
positions must meet a &amp;#147;more-likely-than-not&amp;#148; recognition 
threshold at the effective date to be recognized upon&#13;the adoption of FASB 
ASC 740 and in subsequent periods. The adoption of ASC 740 had an immaterial 
impact on the Company&amp;#146;s&#13;financial position and did not result in 
unrecognized tax benefits being recorded. Subsequent to adoption, there have 
been no&#13;changes to the Company&amp;#146;s assessment of uncertain tax
positions. Accordingly, no corresponding interest and penalties have&#13;been 
accrued. The Company&amp;#146;s policy is to recognize penalties and interest, 
if any, related to uncertain tax positions as&#13;general and administrative 
expense. The Company files income tax returns in the U.S. Federal jurisdiction 
and various states.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Net&#13;Loss per 
Share&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times 
New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;Basic&#13;net
loss per common share of stock is calculated by dividing net loss available to 
common stockholders by the weighted-average&#13;number of common shares 
outstanding during each period.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;Diluted&#13;net loss per common share is calculated by dividing net 
loss by the weighted-average number of common shares outstanding, 
including&#13;the effect of other dilutive securities. The Company&amp;#146;s 
potentially dilutive securities consist of in-the-money outstanding&#13;options 
and warrants to purchase the Company&amp;#146;s common stock. Diluted net loss 
per common share does not give effect to dilutive&#13;securities as their effect
would be anti-dilutive.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;The&#13;treasury stock method is used to measure the dilutive impact 
of stock options and warrants. The following table details the weighted-
average&#13;dilutive and anti-dilutive securities related to stock options and 
warrants for the periods 
presented:&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;table cellpadding="0" 
cellspacing="0" align="center" style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 
44%"&gt;&#13;&lt;tr style="vertical-align: bottom"&gt;&#13;    &lt;td 
colspan="3" style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; text-align: left; 
vertical-align: top"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style="font-size: 10pt; 
padding-bottom: 1pt"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td colspan="7" 
style="font-size: 10pt; border-bottom: Black 1pt solid; text-align: center; 
vertical-align: top"&gt;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; margin-
top: 0; text-align: center; margin-bottom: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;b&gt;For&#13;                             
the Three Months Ended&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman,serif; margin: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;b&gt;June&#13;                                         
30,&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&#13;&lt;tr

10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-
left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;The&#13;Company recognizes compensation cost for stock-based awards 
based on estimated fair value of the award and records compensation&#13;expense 
over the requisite service period. See Note 6 - Share-Based Compensation. 
&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New 
Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right:
 5.05pt; margin-left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Comprehensive&#13;Loss&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&
#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-
right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif"&gt;The&#13;Company does not have revenue, expenses, gains or
losses that are reflected in equity rather than in results of operations. 
Consequently,&#13;for all periods presented, comprehensive loss is equal to net 
loss.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New 
Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Major&#13;Customers&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13
;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-
right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif"&gt;The&#13;Company has no operations during the three months ended
June 30, 2014 and 2013 and as a result no customers or 
billings.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New 
Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Off-
Balance&#13;Sheet Arrangements&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;As&#13;part of its ongoing business, the Company has not participated 
in transactions that generate relationships with unconsolidated&#13;entities or 
financial partnerships, such as entities often referred to as structured finance
or special purpose entities (SPEs),&#13;which would have been established for 
the purpose of facilitating off-balance sheet arrangements or other 
contractually narrow&#13;or limited purposes. From its incorporation on 
February&amp;#160;4, 2004 through June 30,&amp;#160;2014, the Company has not 
been involved&#13;in any unconsolidated SPE 
transactions.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New 
Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Reclassification&lt;/u&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#
13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; 
margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;Certain&#13;amounts in the prior period financial 
statements have been reclassified to conform to the current period financial 
statement presentation.&#13;Such reclassifications had no effect on the 
Company&amp;#146;s net loss.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-

Times New Roman,serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 
10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;The&#13;Company has reviewed all recently
issued, but not yet effective, accounting pronouncements and does not believe 
the future adoption&#13;of any such pronouncements may be expected to cause a 
material impact on its financial condition or the results of its 
operations.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:SignificantAccountingPoliciesTextBlock>
    <us-gaap:UseOfEstimates contextRef="From2014-04-01to2014-06-30">&lt;p 
style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Use&#13;of Estimates in the Preparation of Financial 
Statements&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;The&#13;preparation of financial statements in conformity with 
accounting principles generally accepted in the United States 
requires&#13;management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the 
reported amounts of assets and liabilities, disclosure of contingent&#13;assets 
and liabilities at the date of the financial statements, and the reported 
amounts of revenues and expenses during the reporting&#13;periods. Actual 
results could differ from those estimates.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:UseOfEstimates>
    <us-gaap:CashAndCashEquivalentsPolicyTextBlock contextRef="From2014-04-
01to2014-06-30">&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: 
justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Cash&#13;and Cash
Equivalents&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 
10pt/11pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; 
margin-left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;The&#13;Company considers all liquid investments purchased with an 
initial maturity of three months or less to be cash equivalents. Cash&#13;and 
cash equivalents include demand deposits and money market funds carried at cost 
which approximates fair value. The Company&#13;maintains its cash in 
institutions insured by the Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation 
(&amp;#147;FDIC&amp;#148;), although such deposits&#13;are in excess of the 
insurance coverage. At June 30, 2014, the Company had $1,139,299 in cash 
deposits in excess of FDIC insured&#13;limits.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:CashAndCashEquivalentsPolicyTextBlock>
    <us-gaap:OilAndGasPropertiesPolicyPolicyTextBlock contextRef="From2014-04-
01to2014-06-30">&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: 
justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Oil&#13;and Gas Producing 
Activities&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;The&#13;Company has only recently re-engaged in oil and gas producing 
activities. In accounting for oil and gas producing activities,&#13;the Company 
uses the successful efforts method of accounting for its oil and gas properties.
Under this method of accounting,&#13;all property acquisition costs and costs of
exploratory and development wells are capitalized when incurred, pending 
determination&#13;of whether the well has found proved reserves. If an 
exploratory well does not find proved reserves, the costs of drilling 
the&#13;well are charged to expense. Exploratory dry hole costs are included in 
cash flows from investing activities as part of capital&#13;expenditures within 
the consolidated statements of cash flows. The costs of development wells are 
capitalized whether or not proved&#13;reserves are found. Costs of unproved 
leases, which may become productive, are reclassified to proved properties when 
proved reserves&#13;are discovered on the property. Unproved oil and gas 
interests are carried at the lower of cost or estimated fair value and 
are&#13;not subject to amortization&lt;b&gt;. &lt;/b&gt;At June 30, 2014 and 
March 31, 2014, the Company had $0 and $0, respectively of unproved oil&#13;and 
gas properties.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times 
New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;Geological&#13;and geophysical costs and the costs of carrying and 
retaining unproved properties are expensed as incurred. DD&amp;#38;A of 
capitalized&#13;costs related to proved oil and gas properties is calculated on 
a property-by-property basis using the units-of-production method&#13;based upon
proved reserves. The computation of DD&amp;#38;A takes into consideration 
restoration, dismantlement, and abandonment costs&#13;and the anticipated 
proceeds from salvaging equipment.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;The&#13;Company complies with ASC 932, &amp;#147;Extractive Activities
&amp;#150; Oil and Gas&amp;#148;. As of June 30, 2014 and March 31, 
2014,&#13;the Company did not have any existing capitalized exploratory well 
costs, and has therefore determined that there are no suspended&#13;well costs 
that should be impaired.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt
Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;The&#13;Company reviews its long-lived assets for impairments when 
events or changes in circumstances indicate that impairment may 
have&#13;occurred. The impairment test for proved properties compares the 
expected undiscounted future net cash flows on a property-by-property&#13;basis 
with the related net capitalized costs, including costs associated with asset 
retirement obligations, at the end of each&#13;reporting period. Expected future
cash flows are calculated on all proved reserves using a discount rate and price
forecasts selected&#13;by the Company&amp;#146;s management. The discount rate 
is a rate that management believes is representative of current market 
conditions.&#13;Operating costs are also adjusted as deemed appropriate for
these estimates. When the net capitalized costs exceed the 
undiscounted&#13;future net revenues of a field, the cost of the field is 
reduced to fair value, which is determined using discounted future 
net&#13;revenues. An impairment allowance is provided on unproved property when 
the Company determines the property will not be developed&#13;or the carrying 
value is not realizable. At June 30, 2014 and March 31, 2014, the Company did 
not have any proved oil and gas&#13;properties.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:OilAndGasPropertiesPolicyPolicyTextBlock>
    <us-gaap:PropertyPlantAndEquipmentPolicyTextBlock contextRef="From2014-04-
01to2014-06-30">&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: 
justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Property&#13;and 
Equipment&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;Property&#13;and equipment, such as office furniture and equipment, 
and computer hardware and software, are recorded at cost. Costs of 
renewals&#13;and improvements that substantially extend the useful lives of the 
assets are capitalized. Maintenance and repair costs are expensed&#13;when 
incurred. Depreciation is calculated using the straight-line method over the 
estimated useful lives of the assets from five&#13;to ten years. When other 
property and equipment is sold or retired, the capitalized costs and related 
accumulated depreciation&#13;are removed from their respective accounts. 
Depreciation expense for the three months ended June 30, 2014 and 2013 was 
$8,316&#13;and $8,316, respectively.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:PropertyPlantAndEquipmentPolicyTextBlock>
    <us-gaap:RevenueRecognitionPolicyTextBlock contextRef="From2014-04-01to2014-
06-30">&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; 
margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New 
Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Revenue&#13;Recognition&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;
&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-
right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, 
Times, Serif"&gt;The&#13;Company currently has no revenue from operations 
although during the three months ended June 30, 2014 and 2013, respectively 
the&#13;Company did have a nominal amount of interest received from financial 
institutions for funds on deposit.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</us-
gaap:RevenueRecognitionPolicyTextBlock>
    <us-gaap:IncomeTaxPolicyTextBlock contextRef="From2014-04-01to2014-06-
30">&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-
right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, 
Times, 
Serif"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Income&#13;Taxes&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&l
t;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;The&#13;Company uses the liability method of accounting for income 
taxes under which deferred tax assets and liabilities are recognized&#13;for the
future tax consequences of temporary differences between the accounting bases 
and the tax bases of the Company&amp;#146;s&#13;assets and liabilities. The 
deferred tax assets and liabilities are computed using enacted tax rates in 
effect for the year in&#13;which the temporary differences are expected to 
reverse.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New 
Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;The&#13;Company assessed the likelihood of utilization of the deferred
tax assets in light of recent and expected continuing losses. As&#13;a result of
this review, the deferred tax asset of $31,585,000 has been fully reserved at 
June 30, 2014. At June 30, 2014, the&#13;Company had net operating loss 
carryforwards of approximately $86,706,000 that begin to expire in the year 
2023.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New 
Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;The&#13;Company adopted the provisions of ASC 740, &amp;#147;Income 
Taxes&amp;#148; on April&amp;#160;1, 2007. FASB ASC 740 provides detailed
guidance&#13;for the financial statement recognition, measurement and disclosure
of uncertain tax positions recognized in the financial statements.&#13;Tax 
positions must meet a &amp;#147;more-likely-than-not&amp;#148; recognition 
threshold at the effective date to be recognized upon&#13;the adoption of FASB 
ASC 740 and in subsequent periods. The adoption of ASC 740 had an immaterial 
impact on the Company&amp;#146;s&#13;financial position and did not result in 
unrecognized tax benefits being recorded. Subsequent to adoption, there have 
been no&#13;changes to the Company&amp;#146;s assessment of uncertain tax 
positions. Accordingly, no corresponding interest and penalties have&#13;been 
accrued. The Company&amp;#146;s policy is to recognize penalties and interest, 
if any, related to uncertain tax positions as&#13;general and administrative 
expense. The Company files income tax returns in the U.S. Federal jurisdiction 
and various states.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</us-gaap:IncomeTaxPolicyTextBlock>
    <us-gaap:EarningsPerSharePolicyTextBlock contextRef="From2014-04-01to2014-
06-30">&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; 
margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New 
Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Net&#13;Loss per 
Share&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times 
New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;Basic&#13;net
loss per common share of stock is calculated by dividing net loss available to 
common stockholders by the weighted-average&#13;number of common shares 
outstanding during each period.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;Diluted&#13;net loss per common share is calculated by dividing net 
loss by the weighted-average number of common shares outstanding, 
including&#13;the effect of other dilutive securities. The Company&amp;#146;s 
potentially dilutive securities consist of in-the-money outstanding&#13;options 
and warrants to purchase the Company&amp;#146;s common stock. Diluted net loss 
per common share does not give effect to dilutive&#13;securities as their effect
would be anti-dilutive.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;The&#13;treasury stock method is used to measure the dilutive impact 
of stock options and warrants. The following table details the weighted-
average&#13;dilutive and anti-dilutive securities related to stock options and 
warrants for the periods 
presented:&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;table cellpadding="0" 
cellspacing="0" align="center" style="border-collapse: collapse; width: 
44%"&gt;&#13;&lt;tr style="vertical-align: bottom"&gt;&#13;    &lt;td 
colspan="3" style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; text-align: left; 
vertical-align: top"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td style="font-size: 10pt; 
padding-bottom: 1pt"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/td&gt;&#13;    &lt;td colspan="7" 
style="font-size: 10pt; border-bottom: Black 1pt solid; text-align: center; 
vertical-align: top"&gt;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; margin-
top: 0; text-align: center; margin-bottom: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;b&gt;For&#13;                             
the Three Months Ended&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman,serif; margin: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,
Times, Serif"&gt;&lt;b&gt;June&#13;                                         
30,&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&#13;&lt;tr

    <us-gaap:DisclosureOfLongLivedAssetsHeldForSaleTextBlock 
contextRef="From2014-04-01to2014-06-30">&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New 
Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;&lt;b&gt;Note&#13;3 &amp;#150; Assets Held for 
Sale&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New
Roman,serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times
New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;On&#13;October 3, 2013, the Company entered into a 
Participation Agreement with PetroShare Corp., a privately-held Colorado 
corporation&#13;not affiliated with the Company 
(&amp;#147;PetroShare&amp;#148;), for the purposes of drilling at least one and 
up to two oil and/or&#13;gas wells to test the Niobrara formation to a depth of 
approximately 7,850 feet total vertical depth in Moffatt County,
Colorado.&#13;The estimated cost for drilling the first well (Kowach 3-25) was 
$1,824,460 ($547,338 net to the Company) and if warranted an&#13;additional 
$471,772 for completion ($141,517 to the Company). The estimated cost for 
drilling the second well (Voloshin 3-25)&#13;was $1,982,998 ($549,899 net to the
Company) and if warranted an additional $474,247 for completion ($142,274 to the
Company).&#13;PetroShare is the operator of the wells and two other companies, 
not affiliated with the Company or PetroShare, were also participating&#13;in 
the well.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New 
Roman,serif; margin: 0; text-align: 
justify"&gt;&amp;#160;&amp;#160;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt
Times New Roman,serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 
10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;During&#13;the year ended March 31, 2014,
the Company paid a total of $1,142,237 to PetroShare for (1) its share of the 
costs of drilling&#13;the first well and second well in exchange for a 30% 
working interest (25.309% net revenue interest) in each well subject to 
a&#13;reduction of the working interest to 25% (and a proportional reduction of 
the net revenue interest) if the Company and PetroShare&#13;did not complete a 
business combination and (2) a deposit with PetroShare for costs relating to 
completion of the wells. &lt;font style="color: windowtext"&gt;Rancher&#13;does 
not have a direct ownership interest in the leases since no assignment was made 
to Rancher. Rancher&amp;#146;s only interest&#13;in the leases is through the 
Participation Agreement, under which a dispute had been raised. As set forth in 
ASC 360, these costs&#13;in the amount of $1,142,237 have been recorded on the 
balance sheet at March 31, 2014 as Assets Held for Sale. 
&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New 
Roman,serif; margin: 0; text-align: justify"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times
New Roman, Times, Serif"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; margin: 0; text-align: 
justify"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;On&#13;May 5, 2014, the parties entered into a Settlement Agreement to
settle their claims and, among other provisions, payment of $100,000&#13;(which 
payment was received by Rancher on May 6, 2014). The Settlement Agreement also 
requires payment by PetroShare to Rancher&#13;of $1,042,237 by June 16, 2014, as
well as mutual releases that become effective upon receipt of the final payment.
The Settlement&#13;Agreement acknowledges that neither Rancher nor PetroShare 
admits any liability to the other.&lt;font style="color: 
windowtext"&gt;&#13;Also, Rancher&amp;#146;s board of directors does not 
consider this to be the sale of all or substantially all of 
Rancher&amp;#146;s&#13;assets.&lt;/font&gt; Rancher received the remaining 
$1,042,237 on June 16, 2014. Further, Rancher is not conveying any properties 
or&#13;assets to PetroShare but upon receipt of the final payment from 
PetroShare pursuant to the Settlement Agreement Rancher acknowledged&#13;that 
the Participation Agreement and Rancher&amp;#146;s rights under the related 
joint operating agreement have been terminated.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</us-

Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;&lt;u&gt;Litigation&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p 
style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;A&#13;group of persons who purchased $1,776,750 of securities as part 
of the Company&amp;#146;s private placement offering filed suit&#13;in 2009 
against the Company alleging that securities laws were violated. Subsequently, 
these cases were dismissed and the&#13;Company entered into tolling agreements 
with these stockholders to toll the statutes of limitations applicable to any 
claims&#13;related to the private placement. These stockholders filed a proof of
claim with the Bankruptcy Court in the amount of&#13;$1,776,050&amp;#160;plus 
ancillary amounts purported to be damages attributable to the alleged securities
violations and in June&#13;2011 the Bankruptcy Court found that these claims 
were subordinated to unsecured claims, as such they were settled as part 
of&#13;the Plan approved by the Bankruptcy Court in September 2012. These claims
are covered under the Company&amp;#146;s D&amp;#38;O&#13;insurance policy and at
June 30, 2014 no claims have been filed by these stockholders. 
&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</us-

Serif"&gt;&lt;u&gt;2006&#13;Stock Incentive 
Plan&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New
Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;On&#13;March&amp;#160;30, 2007, the Company&amp;#146;s 2006 Stock 
Incentive Plan (the &amp;#147;2006 Stock Incentive Plan&amp;#148;) was 
approved&#13;by its shareholders and became effective October&amp;#160;2, 2006. 
Under the 2006 Stock Incentive Plan, the Board of Directors were&#13;entitled to
grant awards of options to purchase common stock, restricted stock, or 
restricted stock units to officers, employees,&#13;and other persons who 
provided services to the Company or any related company. The participants to 
whom awards were granted, the&#13;type of awards granted, the number of shares 
covered for each award, and the purchase price, conditions and other terms of 
each&#13;award are determined by the Board of Directors, except that the term of
the options could not exceed 10 years. A total of 10 million&#13;shares of the 
Company&amp;#146;s common stock were subject to the 2006 Stock Incentive Plan. 
The shares issued for the 2006 Stock&#13;Incentive Plan may be either treasury 
or authorized and unissued shares. During the three months ended June 30, 2014 
and 2013,&#13;no options were granted, expired or 
exercised.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New 
Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;u&gt;2013&#13;Stock Incentive 
Plan&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New
Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;Effective&#13;March&amp;#160;29, 2013, the Company&amp;#146;s 2013 
Stock Option and Award Plan (the &amp;#147;2013 Stock Incentive Plan&amp;#148;) 
was approved&#13;by its Board of Directors. Under the 2013 Stock Incentive Plan,
the Board of Directors may grant options or purchase rights to&#13;purchase 
common stock to officers, employees, and other persons who provide services to 
the Company or any related company. The&#13;participants to whom awards are 
granted, the type of awards granted, the number of shares covered for each 
award, and the purchase&#13;price, conditions and other terms of each award are 
determined by the Board of Directors, except that the term of the 
options&#13;shall not exceed 10 years. A total of 12 million shares of the 
Company&amp;#146;s common stock are subject to the 2013 Stock 
Incentive&#13;Plan. The shares issued for the 2013 Stock Incentive Plan may be 
either treasury or authorized and unissued shares. During the&#13;three months 
ended June 30, 2014 and 2013, no options were granted, expired or exercised 
under the 2013 Stock Incentive Plan.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p

$0&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&#13;&lt;/table&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;&amp;#160;&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;The&#13;aggregate intrinsic value of outstanding securities is the 
amount by which the fair value of underlying (common) shares exceeds&#13;the 
exercise price of the options issued and 
outstanding.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#13;&#13;&lt;p style="font: 10pt Times New 
Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 
0"&gt;&lt;font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"&gt;During&#13;the three months ended June 30, 2014 and 2013, the Company 
did not realize any income tax expense related to the exercise of 
stock&#13;options. During the three months ended June 30, 2014, the 
Company&amp;#146;s realized stock based compensation expense from 
granting&#13;10,000,000 options in December 2013 in the amount of $3,694. There 
was no stock based compensation expense during the three months&#13;ended June 
30, 2013.&lt;/font&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</us-

}

}

}

}

}

<html>
  <head>
    <META http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=us-ascii">

type="text/javascript" src="Show.js">/* Do Not Remove This Comment

  <body><span style="display: none;">v2.4.0.8</span><table class="report" 
border="0" cellspacing="2" id="ID0ELE">
      <tr>
        <th class="tl" colspan="1" rowspan="2">
          <div style="width: 200px;"><strong>Assets Held for 
Sale<br></strong></div>
        </th>
        <th class="th" colspan="1">3 Months Ended</th>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <th class="th">
          <div>Jun. 30, 2014</div>
        </th>
      </tr>
      <tr class="re">
        <td class="pl" style="border-bottom: 0px;" valign="top"><a class="a" 
href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.showAR( this, 'defref_us-
gaap_PropertyPlantAndEquipmentAbstract', window );"><strong>Property, Plant and 
Equipment [Abstract]</strong></a></td>
        <td class="text">&#xA0;<span></span></td>
      </tr>
      <tr class="ro">
        <td class="pl" style="border-bottom: 0px;" valign="top"><a class="a" 
href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.showAR( this, 'defref_us-
gaap_DisclosureOfLongLivedAssetsHeldForSaleTextBlock', window );">Assets Held 
for Sale</a></td>
        <td class="text"><p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align:
justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New
Roman, Times, Serif"><b>Note
3 &#150; Assets Held for Sale</b></font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; margin: 0; text-align: 
justify"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif">On
October 3, 2013, the Company entered into a Participation Agreement with 
PetroShare Corp., a privately-held Colorado corporation
not affiliated with the Company (&#147;PetroShare&#148;), for the purposes of 
drilling at least one and up to two oil and/or
gas wells to test the Niobrara formation to a depth of approximately 7,850 feet 
total vertical depth in Moffatt County, Colorado.
The estimated cost for drilling the first well (Kowach 3-25) was $1,824,460 
($547,338 net to the Company) and if warranted an
additional $471,772 for completion ($141,517 to the Company). The estimated cost
for drilling the second well (Voloshin 3-25)
was $1,982,998 ($549,899 net to the Company) and if warranted an additional 
$474,247 for completion ($142,274 to the Company).
PetroShare is the operator of the wells and two other companies, not affiliated 
with the Company or PetroShare, were also participating
in the well.</font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; margin: 0; text-align:
justify">&#160;&#160;</p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; margin: 0; text-align: 
justify"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif">During
the year ended March 31, 2014, the Company paid a total of $1,142,237 to 
PetroShare for (1) its share of the costs of drilling
the first well and second well in exchange for a 30% working interest (25.309% 
net revenue interest) in each well subject to a
reduction of the working interest to 25% (and a proportional reduction of the 
net revenue interest) if the Company and PetroShare
did not complete a business combination and (2) a deposit with PetroShare for 
costs relating to completion of the wells. <font style="color: 
windowtext">Rancher
does not have a direct ownership interest in the leases since no assignment was 
made to Rancher. Rancher&#146;s only interest
in the leases is through the Participation Agreement, under which a dispute had 
been raised. As set forth in ASC 360, these costs
in the amount of $1,142,237 have been recorded on the balance sheet at March 31,
2014 as Assets Held for Sale. </font></font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; margin: 0; text-align: 
justify"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif">&#160;</font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; margin: 0; text-align: 
justify"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif">On
May 5, 2014, the parties entered into a Settlement Agreement to settle their 
claims and, among other provisions, payment of $100,000
(which payment was received by Rancher on May 6, 2014). The Settlement Agreement
also requires payment by PetroShare to Rancher
of $1,042,237 by June 16, 2014, as well as mutual releases that become effective
upon receipt of the final payment. The Settlement
Agreement acknowledges that neither Rancher nor PetroShare admits any liability 
to the other.<font style="color: windowtext">
Also, Rancher&#146;s board of directors does not consider this to be the sale of
all or substantially all of Rancher&#146;s
assets.</font> Rancher received the remaining $1,042,237 on June 16, 2014. 
Further, Rancher is not conveying any properties or
assets to PetroShare but upon receipt of the final payment from PetroShare 
pursuant to the Settlement Agreement Rancher acknowledged
that the Participation Agreement and Rancher&#146;s rights under the related 
joint operating agreement have been terminated.</font></p><span></span></td>
      </tr>
    </table>
    <div style="display: none;">

            <div class="body" style="padding: 2px;"><a 
href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">- 
Definition</a><div>
                <p>Tabular disclosure of long lived assets held for sale. 
Disclosure may include the description of the facts and circumstances leading to
the expected disposal, manner and timing of disposal, the carrying value of the 
assets held for sale, the gain (loss) recognized in the income statement and the
income statement caption that includes that gain (loss).</p>
              </div><a href="javascript:void(0);"

<TYPE>XML
<SEQUENCE>16
<FILENAME>R8.htm
<DESCRIPTION>IDEA: XBRL DOCUMENT
<TEXT>
<html>
  <head>
    <META http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=us-ascii">
    <link rel="StyleSheet" type="text/css" href="report.css"><script 
type="text/javascript" src="Show.js">/* Do Not Remove This Comment 
*/</script></head>
  <body><span style="display: none;">v2.4.0.8</span><table class="report" 
border="0" cellspacing="2" id="ID0ELE">
      <tr>
        <th class="tl" colspan="1" rowspan="2">
          <div style="width: 200px;"><strong>Summary of Significant Account 
Policies<br></strong></div>
        </th>
        <th class="th" colspan="1">3 Months Ended</th>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <th class="th">
          <div>Jun. 30, 2014</div>
        </th>
      </tr>
      <tr class="re">
        <td class="pl" style="border-bottom: 0px;" valign="top"><a class="a" 
href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.showAR( this, 'defref_us-
gaap_AccountingPoliciesAbstract', window );"><strong>Accounting Policies
[Abstract]</strong></a></td>
        <td class="text">&#xA0;<span></span></td>
      </tr>
      <tr class="ro">
        <td class="pl" style="border-bottom: 0px;" valign="top"><a class="a" 
href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.showAR( this, 'defref_us-
gaap_SignificantAccountingPoliciesTextBlock', window );">Summary of Significant 
Account Policies</a></td>
        <td class="text"><p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align:
justify; margin-right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New
Roman, Times, Serif"><b>Note
2 &#150; Summary of Significant Accounting Policies </b></font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"><u>Use
of Estimates in the Preparation of Financial Statements</u></font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif">The
preparation of financial statements in conformity with accounting principles 
generally accepted in the United States requires
management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reported amounts of
assets and liabilities, disclosure of contingent
assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements, and the reported
amounts of revenues and expenses during the reporting
periods. Actual results could differ from those estimates.</font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"><u>Cash
and Cash Equivalents</u></font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt/11pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-
right: 5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif">The
Company considers all liquid investments purchased with an initial maturity of 
three months or less to be cash equivalents. Cash
and cash equivalents include demand deposits and money market funds carried at 
cost which approximates fair value. The Company
maintains its cash in institutions insured by the Federal Deposit Insurance 
Corporation (&#147;FDIC&#148;), although such deposits
are in excess of the insurance coverage. At June 30, 2014, the Company had 
$1,139,299 in cash deposits in excess of FDIC insured
limits.</font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"><u>Oil
and Gas Producing Activities</u></font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif">The
Company has only recently re-engaged in oil and gas producing activities. In 
accounting for oil and gas producing activities,
the Company uses the successful efforts method of accounting for its oil and gas
properties. Under this method of accounting,
all property acquisition costs and costs of exploratory and development wells 
are capitalized when incurred, pending determination
of whether the well has found proved reserves. If an exploratory well does not 
find proved reserves, the costs of drilling the
well are charged to expense. Exploratory dry hole costs are included in cash
flows from investing activities as part of capital
expenditures within the consolidated statements of cash flows. The costs of 
development wells are capitalized whether or not proved
reserves are found. Costs of unproved leases, which may become productive, are 
reclassified to proved properties when proved reserves
are discovered on the property. Unproved oil and gas interests are carried at 
the lower of cost or estimated fair value and are
not subject to amortization<b>. </b>At June 30, 2014 and March 31, 2014, the 
Company had $0 and $0, respectively of unproved oil
and gas properties.</font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif">Geological
and geophysical costs and the costs of carrying and retaining unproved 
properties are expensed as incurred. DD&#38;A of capitalized
costs related to proved oil and gas properties is calculated on a property-by-
property basis using the units-of-production method
based upon proved reserves. The computation of DD&#38;A takes into consideration
restoration, dismantlement, and abandonment costs
and the anticipated proceeds from salvaging equipment.</font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif">The
Company complies with ASC 932, &#147;Extractive Activities &#150; Oil and 
Gas&#148;. As of June 30, 2014 and March 31, 2014,
the Company did not have any existing capitalized exploratory well costs, and 
has therefore determined that there are no suspended
well costs that should be impaired.</font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif">The
Company reviews its long-lived assets for impairments when events or changes in 
circumstances indicate that impairment may have
occurred. The impairment test for proved properties compares the expected 
undiscounted future net cash flows on a property-by-property
basis with the related net capitalized costs, including costs associated with 
asset retirement obligations, at the end of each
reporting period. Expected future cash flows are calculated on all proved 
reserves using a discount rate and price forecasts selected
by the Company&#146;s management. The discount rate is a rate that management 
believes is representative of current market conditions.
Operating costs are also adjusted as deemed appropriate for these estimates. 
When the net capitalized costs exceed the undiscounted
future net revenues of a field, the cost of the field is reduced to fair value, 
which is determined using discounted future net
revenues. An impairment allowance is provided on unproved property when the 
Company determines the property will not be developed
or the carrying value is not realizable. At June 30, 2014 and March 31, 2014, 
the Company did not have any proved oil and gas
properties.</font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"><u>Property
and Equipment</u></font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif">Property
and equipment, such as office furniture and equipment, and computer hardware and
software, are recorded at cost. Costs of renewals
and improvements that substantially extend the useful lives of the assets are 
capitalized. Maintenance and repair costs are expensed
when incurred. Depreciation is calculated using the straight-line method over 
the estimated useful lives of the assets from five
to ten years. When other property and equipment is sold or retired, the 
capitalized costs and related accumulated depreciation
are removed from their respective accounts. Depreciation expense for the three 
months ended June 30, 2014 and 2013 was $8,316
and $8,316, respectively.</font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"><u>Revenue
Recognition</u></font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif">The
Company currently has no revenue from operations although during the three 
months ended June 30, 2014 and 2013, respectively the
Company did have a nominal amount of interest received from financial 
institutions for funds on deposit.</font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"><u>Income
Taxes</u></font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif">The
Company uses the liability method of accounting for income taxes under which 
deferred tax assets and liabilities are recognized
for the future tax consequences of temporary differences between the accounting 
bases and the tax bases of the Company&#146;s
assets and liabilities. The deferred tax assets and liabilities are computed 
using enacted tax rates in effect for the year in
which the temporary differences are expected to reverse.</font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif">The
Company assessed the likelihood of utilization of the deferred tax assets in 
light of recent and expected continuing losses. As
a result of this review, the deferred tax asset of $31,585,000 has been fully 
reserved at June 30, 2014. At June 30, 2014, the
Company had net operating loss carryforwards of approximately $86,706,000 that 
begin to expire in the year 2023.&#160;</font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif">The
Company adopted the provisions of ASC 740, &#147;Income Taxes&#148; on 
April&#160;1, 2007. FASB ASC 740 provides detailed guidance
for the financial statement recognition, measurement and disclosure of uncertain
tax positions recognized in the financial statements.
Tax positions must meet a &#147;more-likely-than-not&#148; recognition threshold
at the effective date to be recognized upon
the adoption of FASB ASC 740 and in subsequent periods. The adoption of ASC 740 
had an immaterial impact on the Company&#146;s
financial position and did not result in unrecognized tax benefits being 
recorded. Subsequent to adoption, there have been no
changes to the Company&#146;s assessment of uncertain tax positions. 
Accordingly, no corresponding interest and penalties have
been accrued. The Company&#146;s policy is to recognize penalties and interest, 
if any, related to uncertain tax positions as
general and administrative expense. The Company files income tax returns in the 
U.S. Federal jurisdiction and various states.</font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"><u>Net
Loss per Share</u></font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif">Basic
net loss per common share of stock is calculated by dividing net loss available 
to common stockholders by the weighted-average
number of common shares outstanding during each period.</font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif">Diluted
net loss per common share is calculated by dividing net loss by the weighted-
average number of common shares outstanding, including
the effect of other dilutive securities. The Company&#146;s potentially dilutive
securities consist of in-the-money outstanding
options and warrants to purchase the Company&#146;s common stock. Diluted net 
loss per common share does not give effect to dilutive
securities as their effect would be anti-dilutive.</font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif">The
treasury stock method is used to measure the dilutive impact of stock options 
and warrants. The following table details the weighted-average
dilutive and anti-dilutive securities related to stock options and warrants for 
the periods presented:&#160;</font></p>
<table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" align="center" style="border-collapse: 
collapse; width: 44%">
<tr style="vertical-align: bottom">
    <td colspan="3" style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; text-align:
left; vertical-align: top">&#160;</td><td style="font-size: 10pt; padding-
bottom: 1pt">&#160;</td>
    <td colspan="7" style="font-size: 10pt; border-bottom: Black 1pt solid; 
text-align: center; vertical-align: top"><p style="font: 10pt Times New 
Roman,serif; margin-top: 0; text-align: center; margin-bottom: 0"><font 
style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><b>For
                                         the Three Months Ended</b></font></p> 
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; margin: 0"><font style="font: 10pt 
Times New Roman, Times, Serif"><b>June
                                         30,</b></font></p></td></tr>

    <td colspan="3" style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif; text-align:

</table>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"><u>Share-Based
Payments</u></font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif">The
Company recognizes compensation cost for stock-based awards based on estimated 
fair value of the award and records compensation
expense over the requisite service period. See Note 6 - Share-Based 
Compensation. &#160;</font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"><u>Comprehensive
Loss</u></font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif">The
Company does not have revenue, expenses, gains or losses that are reflected in 
equity rather than in results of operations. Consequently,
for all periods presented, comprehensive loss is equal to net loss.</font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"><u>Major
Customers</u></font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif">The
Company has no operations during the three months ended June 30, 2014 and 2013 
and as a result no customers or billings.</font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"><u>Off-Balance
Sheet Arrangements</u></font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif">As
part of its ongoing business, the Company has not participated in transactions 
that generate relationships with unconsolidated
entities or financial partnerships, such as entities often referred to as 
structured finance or special purpose entities (SPEs),
which would have been established for the purpose of facilitating off-balance 
sheet arrangements or other contractually narrow
or limited purposes. From its incorporation on February&#160;4, 2004 through 
June 30,&#160;2014, the Company has not been involved
in any unconsolidated SPE transactions.</font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"><u>Reclassification</u>&#160;</font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif">Certain
amounts in the prior period financial statements have been reclassified to 
conform to the current period financial statement presentation.
Such reclassifications had no effect on the Company&#146;s net loss.</font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; text-align: justify; margin-right: 
5.05pt; margin-left: 0"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, 
Serif"><u>Recent
Accounting Pronouncements</u></font></p>
<p style="font: 10pt Times New Roman,serif; margin: 0; text-align: 
justify"><font style="font: 10pt Times New Roman, Times, Serif">The
Company has reviewed all recently issued, but not yet effective, accounting 
pronouncements and does not believe the future adoption
of any such pronouncements may be expected to cause a material impact on its 
financial condition or the results of its 
operations.</font></p><span></span></td>
      </tr>
    </table>

          <td>
            <div class="body" style="padding: 2px;"><a 
href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">- 
Definition</a><div>
                <p>Excess of issue price over par or stated value of the 
entity's capital stock and amounts received from other transactions involving 
the entity's stock or stockholders. Includes adjustments to additional paid in 
capital. Some examples of such adjustments include recording the issuance of 
debt with a beneficial conversion feature and certain tax consequences of equity
instruments awarded to employees. Use this element for the aggregate amount of 
additional paid-in capital associated with common and preferred stock. For 
additional paid-in capital associated with only common stock, use the element 
additional paid in capital, common stock. For additional paid-in capital 
associated with only preferred stock, use the element additional paid in 
capital, preferred stock.</p>

href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">- 
Definition</a><div>
                <p>Sum of the carrying amounts as of the balance sheet date of 
all assets that are expected to be realized in cash, sold, or consumed within 
one year (or the normal operating cycle, if longer). Assets are probable future 
economic benefits obtained or controlled by an entity as a result of past 
transactions or events.</p>

that have the general characteristics of demand deposits. Also includes short-

amounts of cash and so near their maturity that they present insignificant risk 
of changes in value because of changes in interest rates.</p>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="authRefData"

        <tr>
          <td class="hide"><a style="color: white;" href="javascript:void(0);"

        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>
            <div class="body" style="padding: 2px;"><a 
href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">- 
Definition</a><div>
                <p>Total of all stockholders' equity (deficit) items, net of 
receivables from officers, directors, owners, and affiliates of the entity which
are attributable to the parent. The amount of the economic entity's 
stockholders' equity attributable to the parent excludes the amount of 
stockholders' equity which is allocable to that ownership interest in subsidiary
equity which is not attributable to the parent (noncontrolling interest, 
minority interest). This excludes temporary equity and is sometimes called 
permanent equity.</p>
              </div><a href="javascript:void(0);" 
onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">+ References</a><div style="display: 
none;">

          <td class="hide"><a style="color: white;" href="javascript:void(0);" 
onclick="top.Show.hideAR();">X</a></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>
            <div class="body" style="padding: 2px;"><a 
href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">- 
Definition</a><div>
                <p>The aggregate amount of noncash, equity-based employee 
remuneration. This may include the value of stock or unit options, amortization 
of restricted stock or units, and adjustment for officers' compensation. As 
noncash, this element is an add back when calculating net cash generated by 
operating activities using the indirect method.</p>
              </div><a href="javascript:void(0);" 
onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">+ References</a><div style="display: 
none;">
                <p>Reference 1: 
http://www.xbrl.org/2003/role/presentationRef<br><br> -Publisher FASB<br><br> 
-Name Accounting Standards Codification<br><br> -Topic 230<br><br> -SubTopic 
10<br><br> -Section 45<br><br> -Paragraph 28<br><br> -Subparagraph (a)<br><br> 
-URI http://asc.fasb.org/extlink&amp;oid=31042434&amp;loc=d3e3602-
108585<br><br><br><br></p>
              </div><a href="javascript:void(0);"

which are now held in the treasury.</p>

      <table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="authRefData" 
style="display: none;" id="defref_us-gaap_StockholdersEquity">
        <tr>
          <td class="hide"><a style="color: white;" href="javascript:void(0);"
onclick="top.Show.hideAR();">X</a></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>
            <div class="body" style="padding: 2px;"><a 
href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">- 
Definition</a><div>
                <p>Total of all stockholders' equity (deficit) items, net of 
receivables from officers, directors, owners, and affiliates of the entity which
are attributable to the parent. The amount of the economic entity's 
stockholders' equity attributable to the parent excludes the amount of 
stockholders' equity which is allocable to that ownership interest in subsidiary
equity which is not attributable to the parent (noncontrolling interest, 
minority interest). This excludes temporary equity and is sometimes called 
permanent equity.</p>
              </div><a href="javascript:void(0);" 
onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">+ References</a><div style="display: 
none;">

<DOCUMENT>
<TYPE>XML
<SEQUENCE>21
<FILENAME>Show.js
<DESCRIPTION>IDEA: XBRL DOCUMENT
<TEXT>
/**
 * Rivet Software Inc.
 *
 * @copyright Copyright (c) 2006-2011 Rivet Software, Inc. All rights reserved.
 * Version 2.4.0.3
 *
 */
var Show = {};
Show.LastAR = null,
Show.hideAR = function(){
Show.LastAR.style.display = 'none';
};
Show.showAR = function ( link, id, win ){
if( Show.LastAR ){
Show.hideAR();
}
var ref = link;
do {
ref = ref.nextSibling;
} while (ref && ref.nodeName != 'TABLE');
if (!ref || ref.nodeName != 'TABLE') {
var tmp = win ?
win.document.getElementById(id) :
document.getElementById(id);
if( tmp ){
ref = tmp.cloneNode(true);
ref.id = '';
link.parentNode.appendChild(ref);
}
}
if( ref ){
ref.style.display = 'block';
Show.LastAR = ref;
}
};
Show.toggleNext = function( link ){
var ref = link;
do{
ref = ref.nextSibling;
}while( ref.nodeName != 'DIV' );
if( ref.style &&
ref.style.display &&
ref.style.display == 'none' ){
ref.style.display = 'block';
if( link.textContent ){
link.textContent = link.textContent.replace( '+', '-' );
}else{
link.innerText = link.innerText.replace( '+', '-' );
}
}else{
ref.style.display = 'none';
if( link.textContent ){
link.textContent = link.textContent.replace( '-', '+' );
}else{
link.innerText = link.innerText.replace( '-', '+' );
}
}
};
</TEXT>
</DOCUMENT>

Definition</a><div>
                <p>The current period expense charged against earnings on long-
lived, physical assets not used in production, and which are not intended for 
resale, to allocate or recognize the cost of such assets over their useful 
lives; or to record the reduction in book value of an intangible asset over the 
benefit period of such asset; or to reflect consumption during the period of an 
asset that is not used in production.</p>

          <td>
            <div class="body" style="padding: 2px;"><a 
href="javascript:void(0);" onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">- 
Definition</a><div>
                <p>The amount of net income or loss for the period per each 
share in instances when basic and diluted earnings per share are the same amount
and reported as a single line item on the face of the financial statements.  
Basic earnings per share is the amount of net income or loss for the period per 
each share of common stock or unit outstanding during the reporting period.  
Diluted earnings per share includes the amount of net income or loss for the 
period available to each share of common stock or common unit outstanding during
the reporting period and to each share or unit that would have been outstanding 
assuming the issuance of common shares or units for all dilutive potential 
common shares or units outstanding during the reporting period.</p>
              </div><a href="javascript:void(0);" 
onclick="top.Show.toggleNext( this );">+ References</a><div style="display:

during the period. Included in this element is interest derived from investments
in debt securities, cash and cash equivalents, and other investments which 
reflect the time value of money or transactions in which the payments are for 
the use or forbearance of money and other income from ancillary business-related
activities (that is, excluding major activities considered part of the normal 
operations of the business).</p>
